##Ms. Li, who returned from the United States to seek medical treatment, has more questions

In addition to covering up her illness before flying home, she has been criticized by some Chinese-americans.

Recently, a case of imported new coronary pneumonia in Beijing has attracted public attention. According to an introduction yesterday by Pang Xinghuo, deputy director of the Beijing Center for Disease Control and Prevention, the confirmed case named Li, 2008 East West Bank Classic – Doubles arrived in Beijing Capital International Airport on March 13 with her husband and children aboard Air China's CA988.

Pang Xinghuo also said that Li, a native of Chongqing who has lived in Massachusetts (Massachusetts) in the United States for years, said she attended a company meeting in the United States from February 26 to 27, one of her colleagues was later diagnosed with the disease, and she herself developed fever and other symptoms on March 1.

In addition, Pang said Li claimed that three applications for a new coronavirus nucleic acid test were rejected when he sought medical treatment in the United States on March 3,5,10 and 11, that's why she flew back to China from 2008 East West Bank Classic – Doubles on March 12 for medical treatment.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
However, as this case ferments in the public opinion, people gradually discover this Li Mou's problem, may be more serious and excessive than imagined.

For example, a recent report in the Beijing Daily Today pointed out that the 2008 East West Bank Classic – Doubles had taken a large amount of antipyretic before boarding the plane, and concealed his illness from the flight crew, saying that he had no travel companion, he said he was feeling a bit sick and asked the flight attendant to seat him in the back of the plane.

It was not until two hours before the plane landed that Li, who had been running back from the United States to China for medical treatment, revealed the truth, saying that someone from the company she worked for had confirmed that she had a fever herself, but that she had taken antipyretics, said she had a husband and kids on board.

An interview with a reporter from the Global Times confirmed this. A passenger who was on the same plane with Li and whose seat was several rows apart from Li's at the beginning of the flight said that after the plane landed in Beijing, the flight attendant announced that epidemic prevention personnel should be on board to inspect it, so everyone waited for about an hour, i saw one of Li's family get off the plane first. Before the rest of the passengers disembarked.

The passenger added that while everyone on the plane was well protected, many of them wearing goggles and face masks, she described Li's actions as "extremely selfish and inexcusable, and hoped she would be brought to justice. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the other hand, Li's case has also attracted the attention of many Chinese in Massachusetts. According to two local Chinese chat records seen by the Global Times reporter, Li is an employee of Biogen (Bojian) , a biotechnology company in Massachusetts, the outbreak was discovered in early March following a massive cluster of cases at a meeting of the company on February 26.

In these chats, someone also said that Li had been "diagnosed" in the United States, but that she was "not satisfied" with the medical treatment in the United States, so she violated the quarantine requirement and traveled all the way from Massachusetts to Los Angeles, then returned to China by plane, and she lied about being tested in the states.

"How many people are going to get into trouble along the way, " one of the chat logs said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Another person familiar with US air traffic said there were direct flights to Beijing from New York, not far from Li's home state of Massachusetts, but she chose to travel from the east coast to the West Coast and then back home from Los Angeles.

The source said that considering the United States very low mask wearing rate, it can be expected that this route may also be a lot of Li's infection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
But others, who identified themselves as Li's colleague, posted on a forum called North American Chinese e net: "She is already quite serious. The hospital won't admit her and won't let her be treated. ".

The person said he was a close contact of Li, although finally allowed to do virus testing, but was told that "resources are tight, (testing) time notice. ".

"The hospital... has made it clear that if positive has no treatment before he needs to be put on a suction machine, he should rest at home... should we also flee to the country if we are diagnosed? " The person wrote

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Global Times reporters are still verifying the above information, but we checked reports in local US media and found that Biogen, a biotechnology company in Massachusetts, it was true that a large conference was held locally on 26 February, and in the few days following the conference, several new cases of coronavirus were confirmed. This is also in line with the current Li has been confirmed information that she was in the local 26 February to participate in a meeting, some people confirmed infection.

On March 5, Biogen notified the company of the gathering and asked its employees to work remotely, after realizing something was wrong, according to the The Boston Globe. Other media said the company on the 9th to participate in the meeting of the staff at home self-isolation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The employees who attended the meeting and later developed suspected symptoms, the The Boston Globe said in an update dated March 10, the company, which reported the outbreak on March 5, went to a local hospital to get tested for the virus, but was turned down because it did not meet the standards set by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which are overly stringent.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At one point, Biogen even asked its employees not to go to the hospital for tests because so many of its employees went to the hospital emergency room for tests, which had put pressure on the local hospital's emergency room.

Biogen itself reported to local authorities on March 3 and 4 that a cluster of cases had emerged at a company meeting, and asked about testing, but was also rejected for not meeting the test criteria.

But the report added that by March 6, a number of local hospitals had set up temporary testing stations to cope with the increased demand for testing as a result of Biogen's cluster of cases.

According to a March 9 report on a U.S. health information website, officials at the time had agreed to screen Biogen employees who had attended meetings, and Biogen had told employees to stay home and isolate themselves, and wait for authorities to contact them for testing.

After the standards were relaxed for Biogen employees, Massachusetts officials released data on March 9 showing that they had already detected 32 confirmed cases of the company's involvement, it accounted for nearly 80 percent of the state's then 41 confirmed cases.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Since then, the number of "confirmed cases associated with Biogen" has also been part of the local authorities' daily notification of the outbreak, which increased from 32 cases on March 9 to 104 on March 14, it accounted for 75% of the 138 confirmed cases for the day -- as if the Biogen conference had become the "south China Seafood Market" in Massachusetts.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Well, from the above-mentioned information, although we are not able to verify Li's allegation that he "fled back to China after being diagnosed" for the time being, we can find from the above-mentioned US media reports that, li should have known about the outbreak before he returned to China, and had been told by the company to quarantine at home, waiting for official contact to test.

As to why she still went to Los Angeles under such circumstances, hid her illness and took the opportunity to return home, putting her and others'safety at risk, whether this reckless act was really like the post on the North American Chinese e network, because she doesn't think the treatment in the U.S. is working, and it still needs to be verified.
